  <mainDescription>&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Overview&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Rational Functional Tester Extension for Terminal-based Applications (FTE) is used to automate the testing of MVS, VM,&#xD;
    OS/400 and Unix host applications.&amp;nbsp; This tool mentor assumes you have installed the Rational Functional Tester&#xD;
    Extension and have some familiarity with Rational Functional Tester (RFT).&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    From the Rational Functional Tester Extension (FTE) window, you can configure some of the ways FTE behaves.&amp;nbsp;This&#xD;
    tool mentor describes the steps to configure FTE. For more information, see &quot;IBM Extension for Terminal Based&#xD;
    Applications preferences&quot; in the FTE online Help.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h4>&#xD;
    Tool Steps&#xD;
&lt;/h4>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    In order to&amp;nbsp;configure Rational Functional Tester Extension (FTE), you must perform the following steps:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ol>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Open an RFT project and bring up FTE.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Use&amp;nbsp;the FTE menu bar or toolbar to bring up the FTE &quot;Preferences&quot; window.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        In the &quot;Preferences&quot; window, you can set time limits for various ways FTE interacts with the host system, and&#xD;
        specify the default folder for FTE connection configuration files. [link to Tool Mentor for&#xD;
        fte_save_and_load_connection_config]&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        If invalid FTE configuration information&amp;nbsp;is entered, FTE will display an error message warning about the&#xD;
        invalid values.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        This information will be saved in the userprefs.ini file and used whenever FTE is brought up in the future.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ol></mainDescription>
</org.eclipse.epf.uma:ContentDescription>
